E. COLI EHEC - UK (12): (EX SPAIN) TOURISTS REQUEST FOR INFORMATION
*******************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Sun 24 Aug 2014
Source: Daily Mail [edited]
http://www.dailymail.co.uk/travel/travel_news/article-2733024/Our-worst-nightmare-coming-life-Family-contracted-E-Coli-holiday-Spain-call-lawyers-discover-cause.html#ixzz3BIkdP0TR%20


A family of 4 fell "horrifically" ill during a Spanish summer holiday which left 2 young daughters in hospital, one in critical condition.

The family, from Bishop Auckland in County Durham, travelled to a resort in Ibiza in June 2014 but say the trip turned into every family's worst nightmare when all of them fell ill, and the 2-year-old daughters were hospitalised for days as they battled _E. coli_ [O157].

One daughter spent 21 days in Royal Victoria Hospital in Newcastle and needed dialysis The toddlers have now been diagnosed with hemolytic uremic syndrome, a condition related to _E. coli_ [O157] which can cause kidney failure due to a breakdown of red blood cells.

The family arrived at the resort, in the Playa Las Cana area of Ibiza on 1 Jun 2014 for an 11-day break, but within days, all of them began suffering from symptoms of sickness, diarrhea and stomach cramps. The father and the daughters were all diagnosed as suffering with _E. coli_ O157 on their return, and the girls' symptoms were so severe that they were admitted to the Royal Victoria Hospital in Newcastle.

One daughter, who was 2 years old in July 2014, was discharged after 6 days, but the other, who turns 3 years old in August 2014, spent 21 days in hospital and needed dialysis to help her kidneys function properly.

